<div class="text-block row">
	<div class="large-8 columns large-offset-2">
		<h4>Usability Research</h4>
		<p>Before designing, I researched information published from trusted usability firms and other experts in the space. Here were a few snippets of research that I found particularly interesting:</p>
		<h5>One-page checkouts not necessarily superior</h5>
		<blockquote>
		"...we found that users in general had relatively few problems navigating between multiple steps (as long as a few simple guidelines are adhered to) – the usability issues were primarily caused by what the customer had to do at each step."
		<br>
		–<a href="http://baymard.com/blog/one-page-checkout">Baymard</a>
		</blockquote>
		<blockquote>
		"Each of the forms we tested had a 100% pass rate. While our study was small, it did seem to indicate that simply porting the same questions from one long web page to several web pages or to an accordion form isn't likely to significantly increase conversion. Since then, I've seen this hold true in larger quantitative tests as well."
		<br>
		–<a href="http://www.lukew.com/ ff/entry.asp?1579">Luke W.</a>
		<br></blockquote>
		<h5>Visually Reinforce Credit Card Fields</h5>
		<blockquote>
		"One way to increase the perceived security of sensitive fields is to visually encapsulate them. This can be achieved by the use of borders, background colors, shading, and other visual styling that will make one part of the form seem more robust than the rest."
		<br>
		–<a href="http://baymard.com/blog/visually-reinforce-sensitive-fields">Baymard</a></blockquote>
		<br><br>
		<h5>Which Site Seal Do People Trust the Most?</h5>
		<blockquote>
		"So Should I Just Use Norton? It depends. Yes, if you just want a single site seal, although McAfee does not lack that far behind. However, if you want to go all in you may consider investing in three site seals: a Norton SSL seal to indicate an encrypted connection, a McAfee seal to indicate a clean, non- infected “hacker safe” site, and finally either a BBB Accredited or TRUSTe seal for establishing trust in consumer relations."
		<br>
		–<a href="http://baymard.com/blog/site-seal-trust">Baymard</a></blockquote>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="divider"></div>

<div class="text-block row">
	<div class="large-8 columns large-offset-2">
		<h4>UX Recommendations</h4>
		<p>For checkout, I also used these to point out that the bulk of the usability issues stemmed from the existing desktop experience, and that those problems would have to be solved at the source if we were to maintain a webview for native.</p>
		<h5>Recommendations:</h5>
		<ul class="disc">
			<li>Relaxed address validation rules and re-layout the page. Instead of communicating that the user has made an error, provide the new address as a gentle suggestion.</li>
			<li>Use smart defaults.</li>
				<ul>
					<li>Prepopulate all input fields with information we have in the system (e.g. the user’s first and last name)</li>
					<li>Use zip code to pre-fill city and state.</li>
					<li>When a user elects to change shipping and payment method from the Review & Submit page, input fields should remain pre-filled for easy editing.</li>
					<li>“Use Shipping Address as Billing Address” should be checked by default; unless checked, billing address input fields should remain hidden.</li>
				</ul>
			<li>Hide payment input fields when Paypal is selected as payment method.</li>
			<li>Provide a better pathway from expired carts – i.e., provide user functionality to re-add expired items back to the cart.</li>
			<li>Real-time error validation for input fields.</li>
			<li>Remove unnecessary input fields, like phone number for billing section.</li>
			<li>By default, save shipping address and billing method (but need to double check that it doesn’t contradict terms)</li>
			<li>Allow users to exit out of "Add New Shipping Address."</li>
			<li>Invoke numbers-only keyboard when appropriate.</li>
			<li>Visual change: Shorter forms (for less scrolling) while increasing padding for optimal white space.</li>
			<li>Preserve standard formatting when inputting phone number, credit card number, and credit card expiration date.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
</div>

